insulin and protein metabolism\par
the present status of protein synthesis within cells has\par
been outlined.  protein is formed in the absence of insulin;\par
the net formation of protein is accelerated by insulin.  the\par
effects of insulin on protein metabolism take place independently\par
of the transport of glucose or amino acids into the\par
cell; of glycogen synthesis; and of the stimulation of high\par
energy phosphate formation.  in the case of protein metabolism,\par
as in certain studies on the pathways of glucose and\par
fat metabolism, these observations reveal striking intracellular\par
effects of insulin in many tissues.  within most\par
tissues the effect of insulin appears to find expression predominantly\par
at the microsomal level.  incidentally, other\par
hormones which affect protein metabolism such as growth\par
or sex hormones appear to act at the microsomes.  the fact\par
that insulin exerts effects on protein metabolism at other\par
intracellular sites as well as the above independent effects\par
leads one to agree that its action consists of a stimulation\par
of multiple, seemingly unrelated, metabolic events.\par
the fact that an immediate effect of insulin on protein\par
synthesis is independent of the immediate need for extracellular\par
glucose or amino acids does not mean that the\par
sustained functioning of cells is likewise independent.  the\par
biochemist is fully aware of metabolic defects in diabetes\par
which are not altered by insulin in vitro, but which demand\par
varying periods of pretreatment of the animal.  it is\par
also known that in diabetes some proteins (enzymes) may\par
be deficient while others may be produced in excess in the\par
absence of insulin.\par
it is suggested that the physician desires at least two\par
kinds of relation between these fundamental studies and his\par
patients.  one is the possible relation of a deficiency of insulin\par
action to pathological processes in tissues which have\par
not as yet been examined by the methods described.  the\par
other is the need for more accurate measurements of the\par
metabolic disorder and its control than such things as\par
urinary and blood glucose.  in developing such future improvements,\par
the place of insulin in protein biosynthesis\par
must be kept in mind.\par
