stimulus overload, action cycles, and the completion gradient\par
systematic inquiries into the origin of certain emotional disturbances\par
of infants show that consistent maternal care is vital for the\par
child's normal physical, psychic, and social development, indeed,\par
for his survival.  the most elementary precondition for consistent\par
maternal care is the physical presence of the mother or her substitute.\par
it has, however, become increasingly apparent that children's\par
development can also be stunted, and that they suffer damage of\par
varying extent by the attention of, and close contact with, a mother\par
who dispenses what seems to be the "wrong kind of mothering".\par
a model of the mother-baby interaction is proposed to explicate\par
the dynamics of the "wrong kind of mothering" and its\par
consequences: my proposition is that the mutual exchanges between\par
mother and baby consist in a give and take of action and\par
reaction between the two partners, which requires from each\par
of them both active and passive responses.  these responses form\par
series and chains, the single links of which consist in what i call\par
"action cycles," each completed in itself and at the same time\par
anticipating the next link.  i designated these seriated response\par
exchanges as the "precursor of dialogue," as a primal dialogue.\par
the dialogue acts as a vector of the baby's development,\par
influencing its direction and stimulating it to adaptive efforts and\par
psychic growth.  it follows that inappropriate mothering (quantitatively\par
as well as qualitatively) results in what is referred to at\par
this time as the "derailment" of the primal dialogue.\par
controlled experiments with animals, findings of experimental\par
psychology, and, lastly, clinical findings illustrate the\par
mechanics of the derailed dialogue and its sequelae.\par
in the cases under review a surfeit of stimulation, a psychic\par
overloading, resulted in the derailment of dialogue.  overloading\par
prevents its subject from completing actions or responses initiated\par
by him.  long-lasting overload results in the cumulation of "incompleted\par
action cycles".  the sequelae of this cumulation are\par
profound changes in the behavior of the individual.  these changes\par
are manifested in a departure from the norms of individual and\par
social behavior patterns that are maladaptive for the individual\par
and asyntonic with his society, that is, asocial.\par
the derailment of the dialogue is triggered, perhaps even\par
caused,\par
by the nature of the social setting.  one setting, over-population,\par
is extensively discussed in connection with an animal\par
experiment, and the implications for the human community are\par
examined.\par
