interpreting roentgenograms\par
of the skull\par
analysis of the form of the skull is\par
facilitated by considering it to be composed\par
of a number of functional components.  for\par
the roentgenologist's purposes, division into\par
the facial or somatic skeleton and the neu-\par
ral skeleton is valuable, as is the recognition\par
of three functionally separate portions\par
within each calvarial bone: the inner table,\par
the diploe and the outer table.\par
the base of the skull is the only por-\par
tion that is preformed in cartilage.  this ac-\par
counts for the unusual appearance of the\par
skull in achondroplasia.  in addition, the\par
base apparently is more closely related to\par
facial and general somatic growth than to\par
neural growth.\par
calvarial bone forms directly from\par
membrane within the cerebral capsule.\par
consequently, the size and shape of the cal-\par
varia directly reflect the form of the grow-\par
ing neural mass.\par
the inner table of the calvaria at all\par
ages is intimately related to the dura mater\par
and directly reflects the form of the dura\par
mater.  consequently, the inner table re-\par
flects the form of the arachnoid mater and,\par
usually, of the brain as well.\par
the outer table of the calvaria serves\par
not only to protect the brain but also to\par
anchor many of the intrinsic and extrinsic\par
muscles of the skull.  its form, particularly\par
in thick-skulled mammals such as the pig,\par
is determined more by the demands of these\par
muscles and of the scalp than by the form\par
of the brain.\par
the principal function of the diploe\par
is to form a lightweight yet rigid separation\par
of the two osseous tables.  in addition, it\par
serves as a site of hematopoiesis; for this\par
reason it may tend to a specific volume at a\par
given age.\par
the calvarial sutures oppose separa-\par
tion of the bones of the calvaria while al-\par
lowing relative motion between them.\par
when the calvarial bones are passively car-\par
ried apart with the expanding cerebral cap-\par
sule by the growth of the neural mass, their\par
areas are increased by the deposition of\par
bone in the suture margins.  the sutures,\par
however, do not function as epiphyses and\par
have no innate growth potential: removal\par
of a suture does not disturb final skull form.\par
because the calvaria represents ossi-\par
fication of the cerebral capsule, it is small\par
when the neural mass is small.  the de-\par
formity of the skull and the secondary\par
changes that occur in the air sinuses and\par
the diploe can be explained in terms of\par
the functional cranial components.  the op-\par
posite changes occur when the neural mass\par
is abnormally large.\par
the correlation between skull size and\par
intelligence is only fair.  the presence of a\par
brain of distinctly abnormal size, however,\par
may be inferred from plain roentgeno-\par
grams of the skull.\par
premature closure of the cranial su-\par
tures may be due to an abnormal form of\par
the cranial base and possibly of the primi-\par
tive chondrocranium that precedes it.  the\par
abnormality is mediated through the dural\par
fiber tracts that underlie the major cal-\par
varial sutures.\par
