appreciable amount of igg, with gm groups identical with those of the mother\par
(68-70).  the level of the igg of the neonate decreases gradually during the\par
first 3 months (3,27,71), which is generally explained by the catabolism of\par
the maternal igg, whereas the formation by the newborn infant is still\par
inadequate to maintain the original level (16,27).  the best evidence for the\par
transplacental passage is the almost complete absence of igg in the serum of\par
newborn infants from mothers with agammaglobulinemia (3,27).\par
the transfer of the immunoglobulins appears to be a selective process\par
(13, 15).  while igg is readily transferred, there is little, if any,\par
